snippet.textDisplay: I call BS.  This is probably how it went:  "Hey Amazon I want to make a youtube video, give me $24,000 worth of free stuff for $500, and all the idiots watching the video will think that they're going to get lucky and buy up a ton of your returns".   The real truth is that people rarely if ever break even. They're broken products, missing products that were returned empty, missing parts, parts for products you don't even have, etc. And a lot of the pallets are just random misc. things that no one has a use for.  If Amazon could resell this stuff at a discount or as open box, they would, and they wouldn't need to do it in bulk pallets.

snippet.textDisplay:
To all who think it is pure profit, there are things that are NOT being said. There is a reason why that guy sold the pallet to him, rather than doing it himself.

I have a friend who does this for a living and the only way he makes money is that he buys pallets like this in bigger numbers, running an efficient operation. It is back breaking because he does alot of the shipping himself and even then it is slim margins.

Ebay takes between 15 to 20%. If you give free shipping, there are shipping costs. The bigger they are, the most the shipping cost, no matter how much the item sells for. If he charges the shipping, eBay fees apply to shipping costs, even if he makes no profit off it.

PayPal takes 5 to 10%.

You have to buy shipping equipment, like tape, boxes, labels and labor to send these out (not the labor to move them from one place to another) and the labor needs to stick around for as long as he sells the stuff, can take around a month. This is made worse cause most items are cheap and there are ALOT of low priced stuff, not fewer, more expensive things (like Xbox or Playstation).

There are fuel costs to drive things around, he had to buy pallet wrap, and the hours it will take to write all these items up, take pictures etc.

And also....he may only sell 40 to 50% of his items as there are MANY SELLERS ON EBAY. On top of it, even if he doesn't accept returns, he will get 10 to 15% returns, due to eBay's guaranteed satisfaction warranty. Not sure if eBay pays that or is forced on the vendor.

So yeah, his biggest profit will mostly come the money he makes from views on youtube.
